  <!-- Main Content -->
  <main class="lg:ml-72 py-12 px-4 lg:px-8">

    <!-- mermaid charts -->
    <script is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/mermaid@10.9.0/dist/mermaid.min.js"></script>

    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      <!-- Header -->
      <div class="bg-card rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-border p-8 mb-8">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between flex-wrap gap-4">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">
            Client Proposal prepared for Christoph Merrill at Habit Freaks
          </p>
          <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-foreground">
            The Importance Code
          </h1>
          <p class="text-xl text-muted-foreground mt-2">
            Phase 3 — Platform Growth & Business Intelligence
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-right text-sm text-muted-foreground">
          <p>Prepared by</p>
          <p class="font-semibold text-foreground">
            Smiling Dev Consulting
          </p>
          <p class="mt-1">smiling.dev</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <hr class="my-6 border-border" />

      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4 text-sm">
        <div>
          <p class="text-muted-foreground">Project</p>
          <p class="font-semibold text-foreground">
            The Importance Code
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-muted-foreground">Phase</p>
          <p class="font-semibold text-foreground">3</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-muted-foreground">Type</p>
          <p class="font-semibold text-foreground">
            Feature Expansion
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-muted-foreground">Status</p>
          <p class="font-semibold text-primary">Proposal</p>
        </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Architecture User Flow Chart -->
      <div class="bg-card rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-border p-8 mb-8">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-foreground mb-2">Platform Architecture — User Flow Overview</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-4">How users from every acquisition channel flow through the platform, backend services, and marketing stack.</p>
        <pre class="mermaid" set:html={mermaidArchitecture} />
      </div>

      <!-- Executive Summary -->
      <section id="executive-summary" class="bg-card rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-border p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-4 flex items-center gap-3">
        <span class="text-2xl">📋</span>
        <span>Executive Summary</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Phase 3 of The Importance Code builds on the solid foundation
        established in Phases 1 and 2. This phase focuses on three strategic priorities:
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4">
        <li><strong>Capture:</strong> Define and build every user acquisition path — organic search, conference QR codes, B2B group invites, and family invites — so that every touchpoint funnels toward a completed test.</li>
        <li><strong>Convert:</strong> Integrate ClickFunnels, Stripe, and pixel tracking into a tight B2C funnel while building a self-serve B2B onboarding workflow that handles 10-to-1,000+ seat groups with per-head billing.</li>
        <li><strong>Retain:</strong> Lock in users through nurturing sequences, gamification, and group-context engagement — turning one-time test-takers into recurring platform participants.</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Critically, the current platform has a permissions gap: group members can see all the data that an admin can see. Phase 3 introduces a full RBAC system to close this, restricts member visibility to only their own results and high-level group stats, and gives admins the analytics they need to justify their per-seat spend.
      </p>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        This document details each user journey from first touch to ongoing engagement, the exact branching logic for edge cases (existing accounts, minors, returning users), and the technical implementation behind every flow.
      </p>
      </section>

      <!-- User Acquisition Flows -->
      <section id="user-acquisition-flows" class="bg-card rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-border p-8 mb-6 scroll-mt-20">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-4 flex items-center gap-3">
          <span class="text-2xl">🚪</span>
          <span>1. User Acquisition Flows</span>
        </h2>
        <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4">
          There are five distinct paths a user can take to arrive on the platform and complete the Importance Code test. Each path has different context, urgency, and conversion considerations. These flows are referenced throughout this proposal as the canonical user journeys.
        </p>

        <!-- Flow A: Organic Front Door -->
        <div class="bg-accent/10 rounded-xl p-6 mb-5 border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-foreground mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="bg-primary/10 text-primary text-xs font-bold px-2 py-1 rounded">FLOW A</span>
            Organic Front Door (B2C Individual)
          </h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">User finds the platform via search, social media, or word of mouth.</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-foreground">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">1.</span>
              <span>User lands on the marketing site or a blog post. Pixel fires: <code class="bg-muted px-1 rounded text-xs">PageView</code>.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">2.</span>
              <span>CTA directs to ClickFunnels landing page or direct signup page.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">3.</span>
              <span>User enters email, name, phone → account created. Pixel fires: <code class="bg-muted px-1 rounded text-xs">Lead</code>.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">4.</span>
              <span>Stripe checkout for individual subscription. Pixel fires: <code class="bg-muted px-1 rounded text-xs">Purchase</code>.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">5.</span>
              <span>Redirect to the test. Test result is stored as an <strong>individual test</strong> (no group context).</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">6.</span>
              <span>Post-test: results page → upsell to share with friends, nurture email sequence begins.</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Flow B: Conference QR Code -->
        <div class="bg-accent/10 rounded-xl p-6 mb-5 border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-foreground mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="bg-primary/10 text-primary text-xs font-bold px-2 py-1 rounded">FLOW B</span>
            Conference QR Quick-Take → Conversion
          </h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">User scans a QR code at a live event. Priority: minimize friction, capture the lead, convert later.</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-foreground">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">1.</span>
              <span>User scans QR code → lands on a <strong>lightweight capture page</strong> (not the full funnel). UTM params encode conference name + booth ID for attribution.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">2.</span>
              <span>Minimal form: name + email only (phone is optional — conference context is high-trust, low-patience).</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">3.</span>
              <span>Account is created in a <strong>free/trial tier</strong>. No payment wall — they take the test immediately.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">4.</span>
              <span>Test result stored as an individual test. Results displayed instantly on-screen.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">5.</span>
              <span>Post-test CTA: "Unlock your full report — upgrade now" with Stripe checkout.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">6.</span>
              <span><strong>If they don't convert on-site:</strong> Drip sequence starts within 1 hour. Email 1: "Here are your results from [Conference Name]." Email 2 (24h): deeper breakdown teaser. Email 3 (72h): limited-time offer.</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-3 p-3 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-950/30 rounded-lg border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800">
            <p class="text-xs text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-400">
              <strong>Edge case — existing account:</strong> If the email matches an existing account, skip account creation. Log them in (or send a magic link), add the conference UTM tag for attribution, and direct them to retake the test. The new result is tagged as a distinct test instance so their history is preserved.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Flow C: B2B Group Invite (Corporate) -->
        <div class="bg-accent/10 rounded-xl p-6 mb-5 border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-foreground mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="bg-primary/10 text-primary text-xs font-bold px-2 py-1 rounded">FLOW C</span>
            B2B Group Invite — Corporate / Organization
          </h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">A business owner purchases seats (10–1,000+) and invites their employees to take the test.</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-foreground">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">1.</span>
              <span>Business owner creates a group from their admin dashboard. Selects seat count. Stripe charges per-head pricing.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">2.</span>
              <span>Owner receives a unique <strong>invite link</strong> (and optionally bulk-uploads a CSV of employee emails to trigger invite emails).</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">3.</span>
              <span>Employee clicks invite link → lands on a <strong>group-specific signup page</strong> showing the org name and context.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">4.</span>
              <span><strong>If new user:</strong> Signup form collects name, email, phone → account created with role <code class="bg-muted px-1 rounded text-xs">group_member</code> → user is added to the group → redirected to take the test. This test is tagged as a <strong>group test</strong> under this organization.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">5.</span>
              <span><strong>If existing user:</strong> System detects the email, prompts login (or sends magic link) → user is added to the group → prompted to take the test <em>again</em>. This new test is stored as a distinct <strong>group test</strong>, separate from any prior individual tests.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">6.</span>
              <span>Test completes → member sees their own result. <strong>They do NOT see</strong> other members' results, the admin dashboard, or the full group analytics. They see: their result, the general type-spread of the group (e.g., "34% Connector, 22% Achiever…"), and a list of groups they belong to.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">7.</span>
              <span>Admin/owner sees: full roster, per-member results, aggregated analytics, and trend data over time.</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-3 p-3 bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950/30 rounded-lg border border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-800">
            <p class="text-xs text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-400">
              <strong>Seat limit enforcement:</strong> If the invite link is used after all purchased seats are filled, the user sees a message: "This group's seats are full. Contact your administrator." The owner gets a notification with an upsell prompt to purchase more seats.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Flow D: Family Group Invite -->
        <div class="bg-accent/10 rounded-xl p-6 mb-5 border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-foreground mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="bg-primary/10 text-primary text-xs font-bold px-2 py-1 rounded">FLOW D</span>
            Family Group Invite
          </h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">A parent or family organizer invites family members, including the edge case of minors.</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-foreground">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">1.</span>
              <span>Family organizer creates a family group from their dashboard. Pricing: per-head (same Stripe model as B2B, but with a "Family" group type).</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">2.</span>
              <span>Organizer shares the invite link via text/email to family members.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">3.</span>
              <span>Adult family members follow the same new-user / existing-user flow as Flow C (sign up or log in → join group → take test).</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">4.</span>
              <span><strong>Minor (under 13):</strong> Signup form includes a date-of-birth field. If age &lt; 13, the system requires the organizer (parent) to create the account on their behalf. The parent enters the minor's name, and the account is linked to the parent's account. No independent email or phone is collected from the minor (COPPA compliance). The parent initiates the test for the minor from their own dashboard.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">5.</span>
              <span><strong>Minor (13–17):</strong> The minor can create their own account, but the signup flow includes a parental consent checkbox. The parent/organizer receives a confirmation email they must approve before the minor's account is fully activated. Once approved, the minor takes the test.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">6.</span>
              <span>Family organizer sees all family members' results. Members see their own result and the family type-spread — same visibility rules as B2B members.</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Flow E: Paid Ad → ClickFunnels -->
        <div class="bg-accent/10 rounded-xl p-6 mb-5 border border-border">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-foreground mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="bg-primary/10 text-primary text-xs font-bold px-2 py-1 rounded">FLOW E</span>
            Paid Ad → ClickFunnels Conversion (B2C)
          </h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">User clicks a Facebook, Instagram, or Google ad and enters the ClickFunnels funnel.</p>
          <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-foreground">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">1.</span>
              <span>Ad click → ClickFunnels landing page. UTM params encode campaign, ad set, and creative ID. Pixel fires: <code class="bg-muted px-1 rounded text-xs">PageView</code>, <code class="bg-muted px-1 rounded text-xs">ViewContent</code>.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
              <span class="text-primary font-mono text-xs mt-0.5 shrink-0">2.</span>
              <span>ClickFunnels opt-in page: email capture. Pixel fires: <code class="bg-muted px-1 rounded text-xs">Lead</code>. Lead is added to the email list even if they abandon before checkout.</span>
            </div>
